// TEST: exec_match_or_pattern
// EXPECT: output "low;low;mid;high"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// OR-PATTERNS (`1 | 2 | 3 => …`) — one arm matching several alternatives
// (codegen-completeness P2).
//
// js/ts collapsed an or-pattern arm to a single `default:` in the value
// `switch`, so two or-pattern arms produced *two* `default:` clauses (a JS/TS
// `SyntaxError`) and matched the wrong arm. Go emitted `case interface{}:`
// (a type, not an expression). Python flattened the or-pattern to `case _:`,
// which made every later arm unreachable (`wildcard makes remaining patterns
// unreachable`).
//
// All five now emit a real disjunction: js/ts/go test `(s===1)||(s===2)||…`
// in the if-chain; python/rust use the native `case 1 | 2 | 3:`. The fixture
// covers a 3-alternative arm, a 2-alternative arm, and a `_` catch-all so the
// ordering between or-pattern arms is exercised.
//
// The reducer is named `bucket` (not `name`) because `name` collides with a
// DOM/global in TS's default lib (`tsc` error TS2451) — a fixture-naming
// concern unrelated to or-pattern codegen.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn bucket(n: Int) -> String {
  match n {
    1 | 2 | 3 => return "low"
    4 | 5 => return "mid"
    _ => return "high"
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  println("${bucket(1)};${bucket(3)};${bucket(5)};${bucket(9)}")
}
